<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Why Microsoft Copilot fits therapists and counselors work</h2>
<p class="body">Microsoft Copilot is the right choice when you're heavy in Microsoft 365 and want AI embedded in the apps you already use. For therapists and counselors, this matters because the daily work involves both reasoning-heavy tasks and production work. Microsoft Copilot handles common workflows well in its strongest contexts.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">High-leverage use cases</h2>
<p class="body">Five workflows that consistently produce ROI for therapists and counselors:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Primary use case:</strong> intake summaries, treatment plan drafting, clinical documentation, referral letters</li>
<li><strong>Daily driver:</strong> continuing education prep, practice marketing</li>
<li><strong>Quick research synthesis</strong> when you need to understand a topic fast</li>
<li><strong>Writing acceleration</strong> for communications and documentation</li>
<li><strong>Thinking partner</strong> for complex decisions</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">When Microsoft Copilot beats other tools for therapists and counselors</h2>
<p class="body">Microsoft Copilot has specific advantages for therapists and counselors:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Embedded directly in Outlook, Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Teams — the apps you already use daily</li>
<li>Cost-effective at $30/seat (M365 add-on)</li>
<li>Strong integration with adjacent tools in its ecosystem</li>
<li>Fast iteration cycles for prompting and refinement</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">For most therapists and counselors, the right answer in 2026 is to use multiple AI tools — Microsoft Copilot for tasks where it excels, others for the rest. See <a href="/ai-tool-stack-auditor">the AI Tool Stack Auditor</a> for a personalized stack recommendation.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What to avoid</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Using Microsoft Copilot for tasks where another tool is clearly stronger (don't force one-tool fits-all)</li>
<li>Publishing AI output without human edit, especially anything customer-facing</li>
<li>Relying on Microsoft Copilot for decisions that require human judgment and accountability</li>
<li>Replacing relationships with AI workflows</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

